{
  "summary": "Tokens are the fundamental units of text that language models process. They are chunks of text, typically representing words, subwords, or characters, that are converted into numerical representations before being processed by the model. The tokenization process breaks input text into these discrete units, which are then encoded as vectors for computation.",
  "key_points": [
    "Tokens are subword units created by tokenizers that split text into manageable pieces - they can be whole words, common word fragments, or individual characters depending on the tokenizer used",
    "Each token is assigned a unique numerical ID and converted into an embedding vector, allowing the neural network to perform mathematical operations on language",
    "Token limits constrain model input/output: models have maximum context windows (e.g., 4K, 128K tokens) determining how much text they can process in a single interaction"
  ],
  "confidence": 0.92,
  "possible_errors": [
    "The exact definition of how tokens are created varies by tokenizer algorithm (BPE, WordPiece, SentencePiece, etc.) - the explanation simplified this diversity",
    "Token counting methods differ slightly across models and implementations, potentially affecting practical usage estimates"
  ]
